column1: #Text=# CaLiGraph for Semantic Reasoning Evaluation Challenge
#Text=This repository contains code and data to use [CaLiGraph](http://caligraph.org) as
#Text=a benchmark dataset in the [Semantic Reasoning Evaluation Challange](https://semrec.github.io)
#Text=The paper describing the dataset characteristics and results for well-known
#Text=We use [CaLiGraph version 2.1.0](https://zenodo.org/record/5509912) as foundation for the challenge dataset.
#Text=In particular, we use the files `caligraph-ontology.nt.bz2` and `caligraph-instances_types.nt.bz2`
#Text=We provide sample datasets having roughly 10<sup>n</sup> classes with n in [1,6].
#Text=The datasets and all potentially inferrable assertions can be found [here](http://data.dws.informatik.uni-mannheim.de/CaLiGraph/CaLiGraph-for-SemREC/).
#Text=Please refer to our paper if you are interested in how the sample datasets were constructed.
#Text=We evaluated the following reasoners with our sample datasets:
#Text=To evaluate the reasoners, we used their connectors in [OWL API](https://github.com/owlcs/owlapi).
#Text=The source code for the evaluation of the reasoners can be found in the folder `reasoner_evaluation`.
#Text=As Pellet needs an OWL API version lower than 4 (while the others need a version higher than 4)
#Text=Depending on which reasoner you want to run, you have to use the correct one.
#Text=Further, you have to uncomment the respective reasoners in the `getReasoners()` function
#Text=Alternatively, you can use the two provided jar files to run the reasoners with the datasets.
#Text=First download the sample dataset you want to run the reasoners on, then run the jar file
#Text=and provide the location of the dataset as first argument like this:
#Text=The result is a realization of the input dataset through the selected reasoners.
#Text=Have a look at the log file (in the case of the example: `log_elk-hermit.txt`)
#Text=for additional information about the reasoning process.
#Text=The precomputed results for all the sample datasets can be found [here](http://data.dws.informatik.uni-mannheim.de/CaLiGraph/CaLiGraph-for-SemREC/).

#Text=For [SemREC'22](https://semrec.github.io) at the [International Semantic Web Conference 2022 (ISWC'22)](https://iswc2022.semanticweb.org) we provide [CaLiGraph](http://caligraph.org) as an additional challenge dataset for the participants of Task 2 (Systems).
#Text=For this purpose, we use the subsets `clg_10e4`, `clg_10e5`, and `clg_full` and split their inferrable assertions into training, validation, and test files.
#Text=These files are used to train and evaluate neuro-symbolic reasoners.
#Text=Below you find the statistics of the training, validation, and test splits of the datasets with respect to assertion types.
#Text=For statistics about the original datasets, refer to [our publication](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2110.05028.pdf) from SemREC'21.
#Text=The code that is used to create the splits and the statistics is located in [this notebook](CaLiGraph-for-SemREC-2022-train-val-test-split.ipynb).
